revision.text:
The '''absence of good''' ({{lang-la|privatio boni}}) is a [[theology|theological]] [[doctrine]] that evil, unlike good, is insubstantial, so that thinking of it as an entity is misleading. Instead, evil is rather the absence or lack ("[[privation]]") of good.<ref>{{cite book|last=Aquinas|first=Thomas|title=A Summa of the Summa|year=1990|publisher=Ignatius Press|location=San Francisco|isbn=0898703174|editor=Peter Kreeft}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Menssen|first=Sandra|title=The Agnostic Inquirer|year=2007|publisher=William B. Eerdmans Pub.|location=Grand Rapids|isbn=0802803946|author2=Thomas D Sullivan|page=136}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Teichman|first=Jenny|page=45|title=Philosophy : A Beginners Guide|year=1999|publisher=Blackwell Publishers|location=Oxford|isbn=063121321X|author2=Katherine C Evans}}</ref> It is typically attributed to [[St. Augustine of Hippo]], who wrote: {{quote|And in the universe, even that which is called evil, when it is regulated and put in its own place, only enhances our admiration of the good; for we enjoy and value the good more when we compare it with the evil. For the Almighty God, who, as even the heathen acknowledge, has supreme power over all things, being Himself supremely good, would never permit the existence of anything evil among His works, if He were not so omnipotent and good that He can bring good even out of evil. For what is that which we call evil but the absence of good? In the bodies of animals, disease and wounds mean nothing but the absence of health; for when a cure is effected, that does not mean that the evils which were present—namely, the diseases and wounds—go away from the body and dwell elsewhere: they altogether cease to exist; for the wound or disease is not a substance, but a defect in the fleshly substance,—the flesh itself being a substance, and therefore something good, of which those evils—that is, privations of the good which we call health—are accidents. Just in the same way, what are called vices in the soul are nothing but privations of natural good. And when they are cured, they are not transferred elsewhere: when they cease to exist in the healthy soul, they cannot exist anywhere else.<ref>{{cite book|last=Augustine|title=Enchridion|url=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf103.iv.ii.xiii.html|chapter=What is Called Evil in the Universe is But the Absence of Good.|accessdate=2012-11-17}}</ref>}}
See also: "For evil has no positive nature; but the loss of good has received the name “evil.”" (In: [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Nicene_and_Post-Nicene_Fathers:_Series_I/Volume_II/City_of_God/Book_XI/Chapter_9 The City of God, XI, chapter 9])
Perceptions are based on contrast, so that [[light]] and dark, good and evil, are imperceptible without each other; in this context, these sets of opposites show a certain [[symmetry]], but a basic study of optics teaches us that light has a physical presence of its own, whereas darkness does not: no "anti-[[lamp (fixture)|lamp]]" or "[[flashlight|flashdark]]" can be constructed which casts a beam of darkness onto a surface that is otherwise well-lit. Instead, darkness appears only when sources of light are extinguished or obscured and ends when an object absorbs a disproportionate amount of the light that strikes it. This is illustrated by Lao Tzu in the Tao Te Ching quite well:
{{quote|When people see some things as beautiful, other things become ugly. When people see some things as good, other things become bad.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lao Tzu|title=Chapter 2|url= http://taotechingme.com/chapter-02-being-and-non-being|chapter=Tao Te Ching|accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref>}}
The relationship between light and darkness is often used to frame a metaphorical understanding of good and evil. The metaphor can be used to answer{{fact|date=May 2012}} <!-- It seems that under Wikipedia principles such support-needed tag can't be deleted unless one deletes the related clause, and such broader deletion would be fine too, because no one has been able and willing to support the tagged proposition, which apparently was tagged half a decade ago. --> the [[problem of evil]]: If evil, like darkness, does not truly exist, but is only a name we give to our perception of ''privatio boni'', widespread observation of evil does not preclude the possibility of a benevolent, omniscient, and omnipresent God.
If the [[metaphor]] can be extended, and good and evil share the same asymmetry as light and darkness, evil can have no source, cannot be projected, and, of itself, can offer no resistance to any source of good, no matter how weak or distant. Then, goodness cannot be actively opposed, and power becomes a consequence of benevolence. However, evil is the default state of the universe, and good exists only through constant effort; any lapse or redirection of good will apparently create evil out of nothing.
This doctrine is also supported by the [[Bahá’í Faith]]. [[‘Abdu’l-Bahá]] stated to a French Baha’I woman: {{quote|…it is possible that one thing in relation to another may be evil, and at the same time within the limits of its proper being it may not be evil. Then it is proved that there is no evil in existence; all that God created He created good. This evil is nothingness; so death is the absence of life. When man no longer receives life, he dies. Darkness is the absence of light: when there is no light, there is darkness. Light is an existing thing, but darkness is nonexistent. Wealth is an existing thing, but poverty is nonexisting.<ref>{{cite book|last=’Abdu’l-Bahá|title=Some Answered Questions|url= http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/ab/SAQ/saq-75.html|chapter=The Nonexistence of Evil.|accessdate=2012-11-21}}</ref>}}
