{{Infobox philosopher | region = [[Western philosophy]] | era = [[20th-century philosophy|20th-century]] | color = #B0C4DE | image = Delf013.jpg | caption = Bernard Delfgaauw (1975) | signature = | name = Bernard Delfgaauw | birth_date = 24 November 1912 | birth_place = | death_date = 20 August 1993 (aged 80) | school_tradition = [[Neo-Thomism]] | main_interests = | influences = | influenced = | notable_ideas = }}
'''Bernardus Maria Ignatius "Bernard" Delfgaauw''' (24 November 1912 in [[Amsterdam]] – 20 August 1993 in [[Haren (Groningen)|Haren]]) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[philosopher]].
He studied [[Dutch language]], [[history]], [[philosophy]], and [[Hebrew language]] at the [[Universiteit van Amsterdam|University of Amsterdam]].<ref name="kb">{{cite web | title = Delfgaauw, Bernardus Maria Ignatius | work = Wijsbegeerte in Nederland | publisher = [[Dutch Royal Library]] | url = http://poortman.kb.nl/long2.php?TABEL=T_NAAM&ID=262 | accessdate = 2007-03-08 }}</ref>
In 1947 he earned his [[doctoral degree]] in philosophy.<ref name="kb"/>
In 1961 he became a [[professor]] in philosophy at the [[University of Groningen]].<ref name="kb"/>
Delfgaauw was a prolific writer; subjects included existentialism, young [[Young Marx|Marx]], [[Thomas Aquinas]], [[Immanuel Kant|Kant]], mysticism, evolution, and he developed a philosophy of grammar and of social relations. He also wrote a bestselling concise history of philosophy that was in continuous reprint and got translated into several languages.
During the [[Vietnam War]] it was legally proscribed in the [[Netherlands]] to say that [[Lyndon B. Johnson|president Johnson]] was a killer. In 1967 Bernard Delfgaauw said at a symposium: "Measured by criteria used in Nuremberg and Tokyo, Johnson, his staff members, and generals are war criminals."<ref>{{cite web | title = Johnson War Criminal | work = iisg.nl | publisher = [[International Institute of Social History]] | url = http://www.iisg.nl/today/en/21-10.php | accessdate = 2007-03-08 }}</ref> After that, the Dutch student protesters wantonly changed their slogan from "Johnson Killer" to "Johnson Miller".
