{{Infobox religious biography |background = #FFD068 | color = black |name = Ruben L.F. Habito |image= Ruben Habito.jpg |caption = |birth name = |alias = |dharma name = |birth_date = c. 1947 |birth_place = [[Philippines]] |death_date = |death_place = |nationality = [[Filipino people|Filipino]] |religion = [[Zen Buddhism]] |school = [[Sanbo Kyodan]] |lineage = Harada-Yasutani |title = [[Rōshi|Roshi]] |location = [[Maria Kannon Zen Center]] |education = |occupation = |teacher = |reincarnation of = |predecessor = |successor = |students = |spouse = |partner = |children = |website = [http://www.mkzc.org www.mkzc.org] }} '''Ruben L.F. Habito''' (born c. 1947) is a [[Filipinos|Filipino]] former [[Jesuit]] [[priest]] turned master practicing in the [[Sanbo Kyodan]] lineage of Zen. In his early youth he was sent to Japan on missionary work where he began Zen practice under [[Yamada Koun|Yamada Koun-roshi]], a Zen master who taught many Christians students, which was unusual for the time. In 1988, Ruben received [[Dharma transmission]] from [[Yamada Koun]]. Ruben left the [[Jesuit order]] in 1989, and in 1991 founded the lay organization [[Maria Kannon Zen Center]] in [[Dallas, Texas]]. He has taught at [[Perkins School of Theology]], [[Southern Methodist University]] since 1989 where he continues to be a faculty member. He is married and has two sons.
