The '''Three Obediences and Four Virtues''' ({{zh|c={{linktext|三|从|四|德}}|p={{linktext|Sān|cóng |Sì|dé}}}}) were a set of basic moral principles specifically for [[Women in ancient and imperial China|women]] in [[Confucianism]]. The two terms ("three obediences" and "four virtues") first appeared in the [[Etiquette and Ceremonial|Book of Etiquette and Ceremonial]] and in the [[Rites of Zhou]] respectively.{{sfnp|Kelleher|2005|p=496}}
==Three obediences== The three obediences for a woman were to obey:
# her father as a daughter ({{zh|c={{linktext|未|嫁|从|父}}|p={{linktext|Wèi|jià |cóng|fù}}}}) # her husband as a wife ({{zh|c={{linktext|既|嫁|从|夫}}|p={{linktext|Jì|jià |cóng|fū}}}}) # her sons in widowhood ({{zh|c={{linktext|夫|死|从|子}}|p={{linktext|Fū|sǐ |cóng|zǐ}}}})
==Four virtues==
The four feminine virtues were:{{sfnb|Knapp|2015| }}
# wifely virtue({{zh|c={{linktext|婦|德}}|p={{linktext|Fù|dé}}}}) # wifely speech ({{zh|c={{linktext|婦|言}}|p={{linktext|Fù|yán}}}}) # wifely manner/appearance ({{zh|c={{linktext|婦|容}}|p={{linktext|Fù|róng}}}}) # wifely work ({{zh|c={{linktext|婦|功}}|p={{linktext|Fù|gōng}}}})
